{"_id":"39144570-1a6d-11ec-a708-a3dac38ac98d","postId":"2013_11_taskrun-etiquette-examples-even-in-92009538-82a4-3754-9963-fbe116fda88e","postUri":"https://blog.stephencleary.com/2013/11/taskrun-etiquette-examples-even-in.html","replyTo":"67abdd40-1a5d-11ec-b81f-577b79258b31","authorEmailEncrypted":"","authorEmailMD5":"23448e78d187fba56d8bc263081ac5d8","authorName":"Stephen Cleary","authorUri":"https://stephencleary.com","message":"You *can* use `Task.Run` on ASP.NET; you just don't *want* to. ASP.NET uses thread pool threads to handle requests, so in that environment `Task.Run` causes a thread switch from one thread pool thread to another thread pool thread. `Task.Run` is great in UI apps if you want to offload work from the UI thread to a thread pool thread, but it very rarely makes sense on ASP.NET where it just changes from one thread pool thread to another.","date":"2021-09-20T23:48:15.498Z"}